name: signal peptidase I
reaction: Cleavage of hydrophobic, N-terminal signal or leader sequences
comment: The enzyme is found in bacterial membranes and in chloroplast thylakoid membranes. Unaffected by inhibitors of most serine peptidases, but site-directed mutagenesis implicates a Ser/Lys catalytic dyad in activity [1,3]. Hydrolyses a single bond -Ala!Ala- in M13 phage procoat protein, producing free signal peptide and coat protein. Formerly included in EC 3.4.99.36. Eukaryote signal peptidases that may have somewhat different specificity are known from the endoplasmic reticulum membrane [4] and mitochondrial inner membrane [2]. Type example of peptidase family S26

references.title: Evidence that the catalytic activity of prokaryote leader peptidase depends upon the operation of a serine-lysine catalytic dyad.
A mitochondrial protease with two catalytic subunits of nonoverlapping specificities.
A serine and a lysine residue implicated in the catalytic mechanism of the Escherichia coli leader peptidase.
